<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Delhi</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Where <em>Empires Were Born</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Delhi — the National Capital Territory of India — is not one city but eight cities built on top of each other, each the capital of a different empire, each layered over the last like pages of the world's most dramatic history book. From the Tomara Rajputs who built Lal Kot in the 11th century, through the Delhi Sultanate's five dynasties, through Humayun's Mughal glory and Shahjahanabad's magnificent conception, to the British colonial New Delhi designed by Lutyens and Baker and finally the democratic republic's capital — Delhi has been continuously inhabited and continuously reinvented for over 5,000 years. The city is home to three UNESCO World Heritage Sites: the Red Fort Complex, Qutub Minar and Humayun's Tomb. It is the city where the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan built Jama Masjid — India's largest mosque — and where Indira Gandhi was assassinated at her own residence. Delhi holds the world's second largest concentration of monuments after Rome — over 1,200 listed heritage structures. Delhi is also where half of India's political destiny is decided every morning in the corridors of Parliament, the Supreme Court and the ministries of South Block. But Delhi is also street food — the Old Delhi lanes of Chandni Chowk where parathas have been served in the same shop since 1875, where the best chaat in India is made in a lane barely wide enough for two people, where the smell of kebabs from Karim's drifts across the evening air. Delhi is the city of contrasts — Mughal grandeur and glass towers, ancient mosques and metro trains, Punjabi refugees who rebuilt entire neighbourhoods after Partition and the diplomatic enclaves of Chanakyapuri. It is India's most intense, most layered, most contradictory and most essential city.</p>
</section>

<section id="weather" class="fade-in">
