const placesData=[
  {emoji:"🏰",name:"Red Fort (Lal Qila)",location:"Central Delhi",desc:"Shah Jahan's 17th century Mughal palace-fortress — built between 1638 and 1648 as the seat of Mughal power, the Red Fort's massive sandstone ramparts (2.5km long) enclose palaces of extraordinary delicacy: the Diwan-i-Aam, Diwan-i-Khas, Rang Mahal and the Nahr-i-Behisht canal. India's Prime Minister addresses the nation from its ramparts every 15th August. A UNESCO World Heritage Site and the most iconic structure in Delhi.",fee:["Rs.35 Indians","Rs.500 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🕌",name:"Jama Masjid",location:"Central Delhi",desc:"India's largest mosque — commissioned by Shah Jahan in 1656, built by 5,000 workers over 6 years. The mosque can hold 25,000 worshippers simultaneously. Its three great domes, four minarets rising 40 meters and the vast courtyard of red sandstone and white marble create a space of extraordinary grandeur. The view of Old Delhi from the minaret top — a sea of minarets, rooftops and the Red Fort — is one of India's most iconic urban panoramas.",fee:["Free entry","Rs.300 camera fee","Rs.100 minaret climb"]},
  {emoji:"🏛️",name:"Qutub Minar",location:"South Delhi — Mehrauli",desc:"The world's tallest brick minaret and a UNESCO World Heritage Site — the 72.5 meter Qutub Minar was begun by Qutb ud-Din Aibak in 1193, the very founder of the Delhi Sultanate. The complex contains India's first mosque (Quwwat ul-Islam), the Iron Pillar of Delhi (4th century, remarkably rust-free) and the tomb of Iltutmish. The tapering red sandstone tower with its intricate carved Arabic inscriptions is one of the finest examples of early Indo-Islamic architecture.",fee:["Rs.35 Indians","Rs.550 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"⛩️",name:"Humayun's Tomb",location:"South Delhi — Nizamuddin",desc:"A UNESCO World Heritage Site and the direct prototype for the Taj Mahal — built by Humayun's widow Haji Begum in 1565, this was the first garden-tomb in the Indian subcontinent. The double-domed structure rising from a Persian-style char bagh (four-part garden) is a masterpiece of Mughal architecture. Over 150 Mughal family members are buried in the complex. The Isa Khan Tomb in the gardens is a separate 16th century masterpiece.",fee:["Rs.35 Indians","Rs.550 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🌟",name:"India Gate & Kartavya Path",location:"New Delhi",desc:"The 42-meter sandstone archway designed by Lutyens commemorates 90,000 Indian soldiers who died in World War I. The Amar Jawan Jyoti (eternal flame) burns beneath it. The grand ceremonial boulevard stretching from India Gate to Rashtrapati Bhavan — recently renamed Kartavya Path — is where Republic Day parade takes place on January 26. The view from India Gate towards the Rashtrapati Bhavan at sunset is Delhi's most magnificent civic vista.",fee:["Free"]},
  {emoji:"🏛️",name:"Akshardham Temple",location:"East Delhi",desc:"Completed in 2005, Akshardham is the largest Hindu temple complex in the world — 10,000 artisans carved 234 ornate pillars, 9 domes and 20,000 figures in pink Rajasthani sandstone entirely by hand without using steel. The main monument sits on a platform of 148 elephants. The complex includes India's largest musical fountain show, a cultural boat ride and elaborate gardens. It received the Guinness World Record for world's largest comprehensive Hindu temple.",fee:["Free","Exhibition charges apply"]},
  {emoji:"🛕",name:"Lotus Temple (Bahá'í House of Worship)",location:"South Delhi",desc:"One of the most visited buildings in the world — the Lotus Temple receives over 4 million visitors annually, more than the Eiffel Tower. The 27 marble-clad lotus petals designed by Iranian-Canadian architect Fariborz Sahba form a structure of extraordinary purity. Open to people of all faiths, no sermons or rituals are held — only silent meditation and prayer. The surrounding gardens, the white petals reflecting in the surrounding pools at dusk, create an atmosphere of profound stillness.",fee:["Free"]},
  {emoji:"🕌",name:"Nizamuddin Dargah",location:"South Delhi",desc:"The shrine of the Sufi saint Hazrat Nizamuddin Auliya (1238-1325) — one of the most revered pilgrimage sites in India, visited by Muslims, Hindus and Sikhs alike. The Thursday night qawwali (devotional music) performed by hereditary musicians in the courtyard is among the most powerful spiritual experiences in India. The dargah complex also contains the grave of the poet Amir Khusro, the great medieval composer who invented the khyal and the sitar.",fee:["Free"]},
  {emoji:"🦚",name:"Rashtrapati Bhavan & Change of Guard",location:"New Delhi",desc:"The President's official residence — designed by Herbert Baker and Edwin Lutyens, the Rashtrapati Bhavan has 340 rooms and stands on a 330-acre estate. The famous Mughal Gardens (now Amrit Udyan) open to the public in February. The daily Change of Guard ceremony at the forecourt is a spectacular display of ceremonial precision. The building combines classical European and Mughal architectural elements in what Lutyens called 'Renaissance with an Indian accent'.",fee:["Free (grounds & ceremony)","Garden tickets in season"]},
  {emoji:"🏺",name:"National Museum",location:"New Delhi — Janpath",desc:"India's most important museum — founded in 1949 with objects from the IVC, Bronze Age and onwards. Contains 200,000 works of art spanning 5,000 years: the dancing girl of Mohenjo-daro, Kushana Buddhas, Gupta gold coins, Mughal miniatures, Chola bronzes, textiles and decorative arts. Also houses India's largest collection of manuscripts and a Central Asian antiquity gallery from the Silk Road. The museum is the single best place to understand India's complete civilisational sweep.",fee:["Rs.20 Indians","Rs.650 Foreigners"]},
];

const artsData=[
  {emoji:"🎵",name:"Hindustani Classical Music — Delhi Gharana",location:"Delhi & North India",desc:"Delhi is the historic home of the Delhi Gharana of Hindustani classical music — founded in the 18th century by Miyan Achpan, one of the great gharanas of khayal singing. The Thursday night qawwali at Nizamuddin Dargah, the music festivals at Siri Fort Auditorium, the performances at India International Centre and the IHC — Delhi's classical music calendar is among the richest in India. The city produced Ustad Bismillah Khan, Pandit Bhimsen Joshi performed here regularly."},
  {emoji:"🎭",name:"Kathak Dance",location:"Delhi & North India",desc:"Kathak — the classical dance of North India — traces its origins to storytelling traditions in temple courtyards and found its most elaborate form in the Nawabi courts of Lucknow and the Mughal courts of Delhi. The rapid footwork (tatkar), the pirouettes (chakkar), the expressive mime (abhinaya) and the complex rhythmic patterns (tukra, toda) make Kathak one of India's most technically demanding classical forms. The Kathak Kendra in Delhi is the national centre for the form."},
  {emoji:"🏺",name:"Delhi Blue Pottery",location:"Central & Old Delhi",desc:"A distinctive craft tradition brought to Delhi by Mughal craftsmen — blue-and-white pottery made from a unique dough of quartz, glass and Multani mitti rather than clay. The brilliant cobalt blue and turquoise designs on white backgrounds, often depicting floral and geometric patterns, are fired at very low temperatures. Delhi Blue Pottery has a GI tag and is found in Nai Sarak and Kinari Bazaar in Old Delhi — one of the most distinctive Delhi craft traditions."},
  {emoji:"🧵",name:"Zardozi & Chikankari Embroidery",location:"Old Delhi — Kinari Bazaar",desc:"Delhi's Old Delhi has been a centre of Mughal embroidery traditions for centuries — Zardozi (gold and silver thread work on fabric) and Chikankari (white thread shadow work on muslin, originally from Lucknow) are both sold in the lanes of Kinari Bazaar and Dariba Kalan. The Zardozi work on wedding sherwani, lehenga and kurta involves thousands of individual stitches and can take months. Kinari Bazaar in Chandni Chowk is the world's largest wholesale market for embellishments."},
  {emoji:"📚",name:"Urdu Literature & Mushaira",location:"Old Delhi & Institutions",desc:"Delhi is the historical capital of Urdu literature — Mirza Ghalib lived and died in Gali Qasim Jan in Old Delhi (his haveli is now a museum). The city's mushaira (poetry recital) tradition — poets reading ghazals, nazms and other forms to appreciative audiences who respond to every couplet — continues in institutions like the Urdu Akademi and at informal gatherings. Delhi Urdu is considered the purest form of the language."},
  {emoji:"🎨",name:"Street Art & Contemporary Delhi",location:"Lodhi Colony, Hauz Khas",desc:"Delhi has emerged as India's most vibrant street art destination — the St+Art India initiative transformed Lodhi Colony into Asia's largest open-air art gallery, with murals by international and Indian artists covering entire building facades. Hauz Khas Village's bohemian galleries, the design studios of Mehrauli and the contemporary galleries of Neeti Bagh have made south Delhi a serious contemporary art destination. Delhi Design Week draws designers from across the country."},
];

const traditionsData=[
  {emoji:"🎆",name:"Republic Day Parade — January 26",location:"Kartavya Path, New Delhi",desc:"The most spectacular national ceremony in India — India's Republic Day Parade along Kartavya Path (formerly Rajpath) combines military precision, cultural diversity and ceremonial grandeur on an extraordinary scale. Each state's tableau showcases its culture; military regiments march in precision; schoolchildren perform; and the fly-past of IAF jets over India Gate is the climax. Foreign heads of state are invited as chief guests. Tickets are in enormous demand — book months in advance."},
  {emoji:"🪔",name:"Diwali in Delhi",location:"Statewide",desc:"Delhi's Diwali is a city-wide explosion of light and sound — the markets of Chandni Chowk, Lajpat Nagar and Sarojini Nagar overflow with shoppers buying clothes, sweets and diyas for weeks beforehand. The Old Delhi mohallas light up in elaborate displays; the rooftops of Shahdara light thousands of earthen lamps; the sweet shops of Bengali Market do months of business in two days. The city's air quality concerns have led to growing firework restrictions, but the essential warmth of the festival remains."},
  {emoji:"🌙",name:"Eid at Jama Masjid",location:"Central Delhi — Old Delhi",desc:"Delhi's Eid celebrations at Jama Masjid are among the most moving in India — the vast courtyard fills with 25,000 worshippers for the Eid namaz, the lanes of Old Delhi fill with the smell of sevaiyyan and sheer khurma, and the mohallas of Matia Mahal and Chitli Qabar come alive. Karim's restaurant (established 1913) serves its most elaborate Eid menu. The qawwali at Nizamuddin Dargah during Eid-ul-Adha draws thousands."},
  {emoji:"🎈",name:"Phool Walon Ki Sair",location:"Mehrauli Village",desc:"One of Delhi's oldest and most unique festivals — Phool Walon Ki Sair (Procession of the Flower Sellers) has been held in Mehrauli village since the time of Akbar Shah II in 1812. Hindu and Muslim flower sellers carry elaborate floral offerings (pankhas) to both the Dargah of Qutbuddin Bakhtiyar Kaki and the Yogmaya Temple — a rare example of syncretic Hindu-Muslim celebration. Held in September-October, it represents Delhi's plural cultural identity at its finest."},
  {emoji:"🎵",name:"Sufi Music — Qawwali at Nizamuddin",location:"South Delhi — every Thursday",desc:"Every Thursday evening, the courtyard of Hazrat Nizamuddin Auliya's dargah fills with the sound of qawwali — devotional music of the Chishti Sufi order. The hereditary musicians (qawwals) sing verses of Amir Khusro and other great Sufi poets with an intensity that builds through the evening into transcendent collective experience. This tradition has continued unbroken for over 700 years. Visitors of all faiths are welcome — arrive early, dress modestly, sit on the floor."},
  {emoji:"🌺",name:"Holi in Old Delhi",location:"Chandni Chowk & Old Delhi",desc:"Delhi's Holi begins the night before with enormous bonfires (Holika Dahan) in every mohalla, then erupts the next morning as the entire city turns into a canvas of colour. The legendary Holi celebrations in Paharganj and the rooftop celebrations in Old Delhi are famous. The bhaang (cannabis-infused) thandai — traditional Holi drink — flows freely. The lanes of Shahjahanabad become rivers of colour and the day ends with families gathering for gujiya, mathri and puran poli."},
