const cuisinesData=[
  {emoji:"🥣",name:"Butter Chicken — Delhi's Global Export",location:"Moti Mahal, Daryaganj",desc:"Butter chicken was invented at Moti Mahal restaurant in Daryaganj, Old Delhi in the 1950s by Kundan Lal Gujral — leftover tandoori chicken was simmered in a tomato, butter and cream sauce to prevent waste, and accidentally created the world's most popular Indian dish. The original Moti Mahal (still operating) serves the dish as it was conceived. Delhi's butter chicken is the benchmark against which all versions worldwide are judged."},
  {emoji:"🍢",name:"Paranthe Wali Gali & Old Delhi Breakfast",location:"Chandni Chowk, Central Delhi",desc:"Paranthe Wali Gali in Chandni Chowk — a narrow lane with shops that have been serving stuffed parathas since the 1870s — is the most famous breakfast destination in India. Parathas stuffed with unusual fillings (rabdi, dry fruits, khoya, aloo, gobi, mooli) are served with chutneys, achaar and raita. The surrounding lanes of Chandni Chowk serve Delhi's definitive breakfast: bedmi poori with aloo sabzi, jalebi with rabdi, and Shyam Sweets' famous dahi bhalle."},
  {emoji:"🍖",name:"Mughlai Cuisine — Karim's Legacy",location:"Old Delhi — Jama Masjid",desc:"Karim's restaurant near Jama Masjid (established 1913 by descendants of Mughal royal cooks after the fall of the Empire) is Delhi's most historically significant restaurant — serving the same recipes developed for the Mughal court. Mutton burra, seekh kebab, nihari (slow-cooked mutton stew), pasanda and korma — all based on recipes from the imperial kitchen. The nihari at Karim's, cooked overnight for 12 hours, is considered the standard against which all nihari is measured."},
  {emoji:"🥙",name:"Chole Bhature",location:"Sita Ram Diwan Chand, Paharganj",desc:"Delhi's most iconic dish — spiced chickpea curry served with deep-fried puffed bread. The version at Sita Ram Diwan Chand in Paharganj (open since 1959, opens at 8am, sold out by noon) is considered the city's finest. The chole is cooked overnight with whole spices and tea bags to achieve its dark colour and complex flavour. A deeply satisfying, intensely flavoured dish that has spread from Delhi across North India and the world."},
  {emoji:"🍬",name:"Chaat — The Philosophy of Delhi Street Food",location:"Bengali Market, Chandni Chowk, everywhere",desc:"Delhi's chaat culture — gol gappe, dahi bhalle, aloo chaat, ram laddoo, papdi chaat — is a philosophy of flavour contrast: sweet and sour, crisp and soft, cool and spicy simultaneously in every bite. Bengali Market is famous for its dahi bhalle; the gol gappe of Chandni Chowk are considered Delhi's finest. The 'Chaat Corner' of Bengali Market has been serving the same recipes for 80 years. Delhi chaat is among India's most distinct and unimitable food cultures."},
  {emoji:"🍨",name:"Kulfi & Old Delhi Sweets",location:"Chandni Chowk & Old Delhi",desc:"Delhi's kulfi tradition — dense, slow-frozen milk ice cream flavoured with saffron, cardamom, pistachio and rose — predates modern ice cream by centuries. Old Delhi's kulfi culture: Roshan Di Kulfi at Karol Bagh (since 1943), the kulfi falooda of Chandni Chowk, the matka kulfi of Old Delhi lanes. Delhi's sweet shops (halwais) also produce Karachi Halwa, sohan halwa, petha and the mutton-fat-based meethi bread of the Old City's bakeries."},
  {emoji:"☕",name:"Irani Cafes & Chai Culture",location:"Lodi Colony, Connaught Place, Old Delhi",desc:"Delhi's chai (tea) culture spans the entire city — from the old Irani cafes near Connaught Place that served the bureaucratic and literary class of the 1950s and 60s, to the cutting chai vendors of Old Delhi railway station who serve tea in clay cups (kulhads), to the sophisticated third-wave coffee and chai cafes of Hauz Khas and Lodi Colony. The concept of 'chai pe charcha' (discussions over tea) — popularised as a political concept — originated in Delhi's street-side tea stalls."},
  {emoji:"🎂",name:"Delhi's Biryani & Kebab Trail",location:"Old Delhi, Nizamuddin, Daryaganj",desc:"Delhi's biryani — Mughlai-style, layered, cooked dum (sealed and slow-cooked) — is distinct from Hyderabadi or Lucknowi versions. The biryani at Al Jawahar near Jama Masjid, the seekh kebabs at Khan Chacha (Bengali Market), and the galouti kebab at ITC Maurya are Delhi landmarks. The Old Delhi kebab trail — starting at Jama Masjid, through Matia Mahal, Chitli Qabar and down to Nizamuddin — is one of India's great food walks."},
];

